\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\wrapdefault\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid10836955 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af46\afs26 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\fs26\kerning0\insrsid11555524 \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
This document is the architectural specification, design philosophy, and engineering plan for }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af44\afs26 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f44\fs26\kerning0\insrsid11555524 \hich\af44\dbch\af31505\loch\f44 Project AETHER}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af46\afs26 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f46\fs26\kerning0\insrsid11555524 \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46  \hich\f46 \emdash \loch\f46  a Type-1 hypervisor that delivers a complete, production Android environment on any ARM64 or x86 PC hardware \hich\f46 \emdash \loch\f46 
 with no host OS, no detectable virtualization fingerprint, and full app compatibility.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
It is written to be read as a book rather than skimmed as a reference. Each chapter builds on the previous ones, and the early chapters establish the mental models you will need to understand the later ones. If you are joining this project at any point in
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
 its multi-year development, read it from the beginning. The architecture is internally consistent and every design choice depends on choices made elsewhere; reading out of order will produce confusion that the document cannot resolve.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
The project's defining principle is uncompromising. There is no shortcut between AETHER's Android partition and the host machine. There is no shared file system, no shared driver, no shared kernel service, no shared anything \hich\f46 \emdash \loch\f46 
 Android runs on real or fait\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
hfully translated hardware, invisible to everything else. This purity is not aesthetic. It is the entire technical reason the project exists, because every shortcut taken by every other Android-on-PC solution becomes a fingerprint that distinguishes their
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46  e\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 nvironment from real hardware. AETHER takes no shortcuts and therefore presents no fingerprints.
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sa40\nowidctlpar\wrapdefault\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid10836955 {\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af44\afs32 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f44\fs32\kerning0\insrsid11555524 \hich\af44\dbch\af31505\loch\f44 Part I \hich\f44 \emdash \loch\f44  The Vision

\par \hich\af44\dbch\af31505\loch\f44 Chapter 1. What AETHER Is
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\wrapdefault\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid10836955 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af46\afs26 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\fs26\kerning0\insrsid11555524 \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
AETHER is a Type-1 hypervisor written from scratch in Rust and assembly that boots directly on hardware before any operating system, delivering a complete, production Android environment on ARM64 or x86 hardware. The ARM, which boots and runs without any 
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 awareness that it is virtualized. The second domain hosts a complete Android stack \hich\f46 \emdash \loch\f46  bootloader, Linux kernel, AOSP system services, ART runtime, microG, and applications \hich\f46 \emdash 
\loch\f46  which equally has no awareness that anything else exists on the machine. The two d\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 om\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
ains share only the physical processor's instruction set. They do not share memory. They do not share devices. They do not share kernels, drivers, file systems, or even concepts of time beyond what the hardware timer dictates. They are two parallel comput
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 ational universes that happen to occupy the same silicon.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 The user experiences AETHER as a single laptop that can run native Windows applications and native Android applications simultaneously, switch between them instantly, and use peripherals seamlessly with both \hich\f46 
\emdash \loch\f46  but underneath this surface convenience, the \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 two operating systems have no relationship to each other. Each one believes it owns the machine. Each one is correct from its own perspective.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sa40\nowidctlpar\wrapdefault\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid10836955 {\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af44\afs32 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f44\fs32\kerning0\insrsid11555524 \hich\af44\dbch\af31505\loch\f44 Chapter 2. Why AETHER Exists
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\wrapdefault\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid10836955 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af46\afs26 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\fs26\kerning0\insrsid11555524 \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 Every Android-on-PC product that exists today \hich\f46 
\emdash \loch\f46  BlueStacks, LDPlayer, NoxPlayer, MEmu, Waydroid, Genymotion, Android Studio's emulator, and the rest \hich\f46 \emdash \loch\f46  makes architectural compromises that produce detectable seams. They allow file system sharing for drag-a
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
nd-drop convenience. They proxy graphics calls through the host's graphics driver. They route Android's network through the host's network stack. They simulate sensors with simple noise generators that don't follow real physical models. They use generic d
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 ev\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
ice identifiers that anti-cheat systems can recognize. Each compromise saves engineering time and produces a usable product, but each compromise also introduces a place where the Android environment behaves differently than it would on real Android hardwa
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 re. Software designed to detect these differences \hich\f46 \emdash \loch\f46  anti-cheat systems, banking apps, DRM systems \hich\f46 \emdash \loch\f46  can find them.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
AETHER's reason for existing is to take none of these compromises. By driving the boundary between Windows and Android down to the silicon itself, every layer above the silicon is genuinely Android, talking to genuinely simulated Android hardware that res
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 ponds with genuinely physical fidelity. There is no place for a fingerprint to form, because there is no place where Windows leaks through.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 The practical consequence is an Android environment in which apps cannot tell they are not running on a real device, because at every level of inspection they are running on a real device \hich\f46 \emdash \loch\f46 
 a real ARM64 processor, a real GPU partition, real memory, real s\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 torage, real network \hich\f46 \emdash \loch\f46  just one whose top-level identity has been defined by the hypervisor rather than by a phone manufacturer.

\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sa40\nowidctlpar\wrapdefault\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid10836955 {\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af44\afs32 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f44\fs32\kerning0\insrsid11555524 \hich\af44\dbch\af31505\loch\f44 Chapter 3. The Non-Negotiables
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\wrapdefault\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid10836955 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af46\afs26 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\fs26\kerning0\insrsid11555524 \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
The following design constraints are inviolable. Every engineering decision in AETHER must satisfy all of them simultaneously. If a proposed feature would violate any of them, the feature is rejected, no matter how convenient it would be.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
The Android partition must never depend on any host OS or external system for the purpose of accessing resources. Every resource the Android partition uses must be either dedicated to it via hardware passthrough or simulated by the hypervisor's internal v
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 irtual device subsystem.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 No software running outside AETHER's Android partition must ever have visibility into the Android partition's memory, devices, or execution state. From the Android partition's perspective, it owns the entire machine.

\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
The hypervisor itself must be invisible to the Android partition at the level of normal operation. Android can detect virtualization only through deliberate ARM64 instructions that the architecture exposes for that purpose, and even those signals must be 
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 configured to match what real ARM64 hardware would report.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
There is no "host" in AETHER. The hypervisor is not a host. The hypervisor is a referee that allocates resources at boot and then steps out of the way. The Android partition is the sole guest. The hypervisor is referee only.
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sa40\nowidctlpar\wrapdefault\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid10836955 {\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af44\afs32 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f44\fs32\kerning0\insrsid11555524 \hich\af44\dbch\af31505\loch\f44 Part II \hich\f44 \emdash \loch\f44  The Silicon

\par \hich\af44\dbch\af31505\loch\f44 Chapter 4. ARM64 As The Substrate
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\wrapdefault\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid10836955 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af46\afs26 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\fs26\kerning0\insrsid11555524 \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
The ARM64 architecture, formally called AArch64, is the only thing AETHER assumes exists. Everything else is built on top of it. Understanding what ARM64 provides at the hardware level is therefore essential to understanding every other part of this docum
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 ent.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
An ARM64 processor implements a specific instruction set defined in the ARM Architecture Reference Manual. The reference manual is a public document of approximately twelve thousand pages, and it is the only specification AETHER treats as authoritative fo
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
r the hardware layer. Every behavior the hypervisor depends on is something the reference manual guarantees. Every behavior the hypervisor exposes to its guests is something the reference manual describes for real hardware.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
The processor has thirty-one general-purpose sixty-four-bit registers, a stack pointer, a program counter, and a register file for floating-point and SIMD operations. It has a memory management unit that translates virtual addresses to physical addresses 
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 through page tables. It has a generic interrupt controller that delivers signals from hardware to software. It has architectural timers that count cycles and elapsed time. These are the primitives. Everything else 
\hich\f46 \emdash \loch\f46  operating systems, applications, user e\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 xp\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 eriences \hich\f46 \emdash \loch\f46  is constructed from them.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sa40\nowidctlpar\wrapdefault\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid10836955 {\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af44\afs32 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f44\fs32\kerning0\insrsid11555524 \hich\af44\dbch\af31505\loch\f44 Chapter 5. Exception Levels
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\wrapdefault\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid10836955 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af46\afs26 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\fs26\kerning0\insrsid11555524 \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
The ARM64 architecture defines a hierarchy of privilege called exception levels, numbered from zero to three. Code running at a higher exception level can do things that code at a lower level cannot. This hierarchy is enforced by the processor itself in h
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 ardware, not by software, and is the foundation of all isolation in AETHER.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
Exception Level 0, written EL0, is the level at which application code runs. An app like Free Fire executes its instructions at EL0. At this level, the processor disallows any instruction that would affect another process or the operating system. EL0 is t
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 he lowest privilege; everything above it is more privileged.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
Exception Level 1, written EL1, is the level at which operating system kernels run. The Linux kernel inside the Android partition runs at EL1. The Windows NT kernel inside the Windows partition also runs at EL1. At this level, the processor allows access 
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 to page tables, interrupt configuration, and other resources that user code cannot touch. But EL1 cannot reach above itself.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
Exception Level 2, written EL2, is the level designed specifically for hypervisors. AETHER runs at EL2. From this level, AETHER can intercept and control what happens at EL1 and EL0 in either guest. AETHER configures a second stage of address translation,
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
 called Stage 2, that sits between the guest's view of physical memory and the actual physical memory of the machine. This is how AETHER ensures that when Android writes to what it thinks is physical address 0x40000000, the write actually lands somewhere 
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 in\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46  the memory region AETHER has assigned to Android, not somewhere in Windows's memory.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 Exception Level 3, written EL3, is the level at which secure firmware runs. AETHER does not run at EL3. The system's existing firmware \hich\f46 \emdash \loch\f46  typically ARM Trusted Firmware on ARM laptops \hich\f46 
\emdash \loch\f46  runs at EL3 and remains in place. AETHER cooperates with EL3 firmware \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 during boot but does not replace it.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sa40\nowidctlpar\wrapdefault\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid10836955 {\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af44\afs32 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f44\fs32\kerning0\insrsid11555524 \hich\af44\dbch\af31505\loch\f44 Chapter 6. The Virtualization Extensions
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\wrapdefault\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid10836955 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af46\afs26 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\fs26\kerning0\insrsid11555524 \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
AETHER's existence is made possible by a specific set of optional features in the ARM64 architecture called the Virtualization Extensions, often abbreviated VHE in their newer form. These features include the EL2 execution mode itself, the Stage 2 transla
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
tion tables that allow nested address translation, the virtual interrupt controller interface that lets the hypervisor inject and route interrupts to guests, and the system register trapping mechanisms that let the hypervisor catch sensitive operations pe
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 rf\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 ormed by guests.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
The virtualization extensions are present and enabled on Snapdragon X Elite, Apple Silicon, AWS Graviton, and most other modern ARM64 systems-on-chip. AETHER will not run on processors that lack these extensions. The build system explicitly checks for the
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 m and refuses to produce a hypervisor binary for processors that cannot support virtualization.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 When a guest operating system at EL1 attempts to perform a sensitive operation \hich\f46 \emdash \loch\f46 
 for instance, modifying its own page tables in a way that would conflict with the hypervisor's Stage 2 translation \hich\f46 \emdash \loch\f46  the processor automatically traps to EL2, transferring co\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
ntrol to AETHER. AETHER inspects the operation, decides whether to allow it, modifies its parameters if necessary, and either performs the operation on the guest's behalf or returns control to the guest with the operation completed. The guest never knows 
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 th\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 is happened. From the guest's perspective, time simply passed slightly more slowly than expected for that one instruction.
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sa40\nowidctlpar\wrapdefault\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid10836955 {\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af44\afs32 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f44\fs32\kerning0\insrsid11555524 \hich\af44\dbch\af31505\loch\f44 Part III \hich\f44 \emdash \loch\f44 
 The Hypervisor
\par \hich\af44\dbch\af31505\loch\f44 Chapter 7. Boot
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\wrapdefault\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid10836955 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af46\afs26 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\fs26\kerning0\insrsid11555524 \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
When the machine is powered on, control passes through a sequence of firmware stages defined by the platform's manufacturer. The first stage is the boot ROM, baked into silicon and unchangeable. The second stage is the platform firmware \hich\f46 \emdash 
\loch\f46  UEFI on most ARM\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46  laptops \hich\f46 \emdash \loch\f46 
 which initializes RAM, storage, and the bootable device tree. The third stage is the EL3 secure firmware, which establishes the secure world and the chain of trust.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
AETHER inserts itself at the fourth stage, replacing what would normally be the Windows boot manager. The platform firmware loads AETHER as the bootable EFI image. AETHER takes control at EL2 and immediately performs three operations in sequence.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
First, AETHER discovers the machine's hardware inventory by parsing the firmware-provided ACPI tables and device tree, building an internal map of every CPU core, memory region, GPU, network interface, storage controller, USB controller, and peripheral th
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 e machine contains. This inventory becomes the basis for resource partitioning.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 Second, AETHER reads its own configuration from a small partition on the system's primary storage device. The configuration specifies how resources should be divided between Windows and Android \hich\f46 \emdash \loch\f46 
 how many CPU cores each guest receives, how much memory, wh\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 ich GPU partition, which network interface, which storage region, and so on. This configuration is established at install time and rarely changes.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
Third, AETHER constructs the initial state for both guests. It creates Stage 2 page tables that map each guest's view of physical memory to the actual machine memory regions assigned to it. It configures the virtual interrupt controller to route interrupt
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 s from the guest's assigned devices to that guest. It loads the bootable image of each guest \hich\f46 \emdash \loch\f46 
 the Windows boot manager for the Windows partition, and the Android bootloader for the Android partition \hich\f46 \emdash \loch\f46  into their respective memory regions. Then it starts \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 bo
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 th guests by transferring execution to their entry points at EL1 in their respective contexts.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
From this moment on, the guests run, and AETHER intervenes only when a guest performs an operation that requires hypervisor mediation. Most of the time, both guests are executing native ARM64 instructions on the real CPU at full hardware speed, and AETHER
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46  is asleep.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sa40\nowidctlpar\wrapdefault\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid10836955 {\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af44\afs32 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f44\fs32\kerning0\insrsid11555524 \hich\af44\dbch\af31505\loch\f44 Chapter 8. Memory Architecture
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\wrapdefault\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid10836955 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af46\afs26 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\fs26\kerning0\insrsid11555524 \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
Memory is the most carefully managed resource in AETHER, because mistakes here would compromise the isolation between Windows and Android. The architecture of memory partitioning works through three layers of address translation, the third of which AETHER
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46  controls.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
The first layer is the guest's own page tables, which translate the addresses an application sees (called virtual addresses or VAs) into addresses the guest kernel believes are physical (called intermediate physical addresses or IPAs). The guest manages t
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 hese page tables freely and is unaware that its "physical" addresses are not the actual machine's physical addresses.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
The second layer is AETHER's Stage 2 page tables, which translate intermediate physical addresses into actual physical addresses (called PAs) on the machine. These tables are owned by AETHER and are inaccessible to either guest. Every memory access by eit
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
her guest passes through Stage 2 translation, and AETHER ensures the translations only resolve to memory regions assigned to that specific guest. An attempt by the Android guest to access a memory region assigned to Windows results in a Stage 2 translatio
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 n \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 fault that traps to EL2, where AETHER terminates the offending access.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 The third layer is the IOMMU, called SMMU in ARM terminology \hich\f46 \emdash \loch\f46 
 the System Memory Management Unit. The SMMU performs the same Stage 2 translation for memory accesses initiated by hardware devices, not just by the CPU. Without the SMMU, a device assigned to\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
 Android could be programmed by a malicious or buggy Android driver to write to a memory address that belongs to Windows. The SMMU prevents this by enforcing the same address translation policy on device DMA operations as AETHER enforces on CPU memory acc
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 es\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 ses. AETHER configures the SMMU at boot with translation tables that mirror the Stage 2 tables, and the SMMU hardware enforces the partitioning automatically thereafter.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
The result is that no instruction executed by either guest, and no DMA operation performed by either guest's devices, can ever touch memory belonging to the other guest. The isolation is enforced by hardware, not software, and cannot be defeated by any co
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 de running at EL1 or below in either guest.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sa40\nowidctlpar\wrapdefault\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid10836955 {\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af44\afs32 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f44\fs32\kerning0\insrsid11555524 \hich\af44\dbch\af31505\loch\f44 Chapter 9. CPU Partitioning
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\wrapdefault\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid10836955 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af46\afs26 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\fs26\kerning0\insrsid11555524 \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
AETHER allocates CPU cores to guests at boot, and after that point, each core belongs exclusively to one guest until the system is rebooted. There is no time-sliced multiplexing of CPU cores between guests. This is a deliberate choice for performance and 
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 for fingerprint purity.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
A typical Snapdragon X Elite has twelve CPU cores. A typical AETHER configuration might assign six of them to Windows and six to Android, although the configuration is adjustable. Each core runs its assigned guest's code at native speed. There is no sched
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
uling overhead, no context switching between guests on a single core, no jitter from interleaving. The core simply executes whatever its assigned guest tells it to execute, with AETHER intervening only for trapped operations.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
Within each guest, normal scheduling happens entirely inside that guest's kernel. Windows schedules Windows threads across its assigned cores. The Android Linux kernel schedules Android processes across its assigned cores. Neither kernel is aware that oth
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 er cores exist on the machine, because AETHER reports to each guest only the cores assigned to that guest.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 This static partitioning sacrifices some flexibility \hich\f46 \emdash \loch\f46  you cannot temporarily borrow Windows's idle cores to accelerate Android, for example \hich\f46 \emdash \loch\f46 
 but it produces a clean, predictable, isolated execution environment that is much closer to running on native ha\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 rdware than dynamic scheduling would be. Predictability is part of fidelity.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sa40\nowidctlpar\wrapdefault\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid10836955 {\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af44\afs32 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f44\fs32\kerning0\insrsid11555524 \hich\af44\dbch\af31505\loch\f44 Chapter 10. Interrupt Routing
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\wrapdefault\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid10836955 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af46\afs26 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\fs26\kerning0\insrsid11555524 \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 When a hardware device needs the CPU's attention \hich\f46 
\emdash \loch\f46  a disk has finished a read, a network packet has arrived, a timer has expired \hich\f46 \emdash \loch\f46  it raises an interrupt through the Generic Interrupt Controller, called GIC in ARM terminology. The GIC determines which CPU
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46  core should handle the interrupt and signals that core, which immediately suspends whatever it was doing and runs the interrupt handler.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
In a virtualized system, interrupts must be routed to the correct guest. If a device assigned to Android raises an interrupt, that interrupt must reach the Android kernel. If a device assigned to Windows raises an interrupt, it must reach the Windows kern
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 el. AETHER must never deliver an Android device's interrupt to Windows or vice versa.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
The ARM virtualization extensions provide a feature called the GIC Virtualization Extension that handles this routing in hardware. AETHER configures the GIC at boot to associate each device's interrupt line with a specific guest. Thereafter, when an inter
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
rupt arrives, the GIC consults its routing table and delivers the interrupt directly to the appropriate guest's virtual GIC, which makes it appear to that guest's kernel exactly as if the interrupt had arrived on real hardware. The hypervisor itself does 
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 no\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 t need to mediate most interrupts; the hardware does it correctly without any software involvement, which preserves performance.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 The few interrupts that AETHER does handle directly are those targeted at AETHER itself \hich\f46 \emdash \loch\f46 
 primarily the EL2 timer interrupt, which AETHER uses to maintain its own internal time, and inter-processor interrupts that AETHER uses for hypervisor-internal coord\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 ination across cores.
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sa40\nowidctlpar\wrapdefault\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid10836955 {\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af44\afs32 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f44\fs32\kerning0\insrsid11555524 \hich\af44\dbch\af31505\loch\f44 Part IV \hich\f44 \emdash \loch\f44 
 Device Strategy
\par \hich\af44\dbch\af31505\loch\f44 Chapter 11. The Passthrough Principle
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\wrapdefault\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid10836955 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af46\afs26 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\fs26\kerning0\insrsid11555524 \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
Every hardware device on the machine must be assigned to exactly one guest, and that guest gets exclusive direct access to it. This is called passthrough. AETHER does not virtualize devices for purposes that matter to Android. The only virtualization that
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46  occurs is for devices that the Android partition needs to believe exist but that don't physically exist on a laptop \hich\f46 \emdash \loch\f46 
 most notably the cellular modem, the phone-specific sensors, and certain phone-specific peripherals. For everything else, the principle \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 is\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46  passthrough or nothing.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
The reasoning is direct. Every paravirtualized device is a fingerprint. A paravirtualized network card responds to register reads with timing characteristics that don't match any real network card. A paravirtualized GPU has performance characteristics tha
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 t don't match any real GPU. The only way to make a device behave like real hardware is for it to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af45\afs26 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f45\fs26\kerning0\insrsid11555524 \hich\af45\dbch\af31505\loch\f45 be}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af46\afs26 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\fs26\kerning0\insrsid11555524 \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46  real hardware. AETHER takes this principle to its logical extreme.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
For the GPU, this is achieved through SR-IOV, described in Chapter 13. For the network interface, AETHER assigns the entire WiFi or Ethernet adapter to one guest exclusively, and the other guest is given a different physical adapter or none at all. For st
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
orage, each guest is given its own dedicated NVMe controller or its own dedicated namespace within a single NVMe drive. For USB, AETHER assigns specific USB controllers to specific guests; a USB device plugged into an "Android" USB port is connected direc
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 tl\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 y to Android with no Windows visibility.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sa40\nowidctlpar\wrapdefault\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid10836955 {\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af44\afs32 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f44\fs32\kerning0\insrsid11555524 \hich\af44\dbch\af31505\loch\f44 Chapter 12. The Necessity Of Paravirtualization

\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\wrapdefault\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid10836955 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af46\afs26 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\fs26\kerning0\insrsid11555524 \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
There are three categories of devices for which passthrough is impossible and paravirtualization is therefore unavoidable. AETHER paravirtualizes these and only these.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
The first category is the cellular modem. A laptop does not have a cellular modem in the form factor Android expects, so AETHER's hypervisor includes a virtual modem device that responds to AT commands and presents itself to the Android kernel as a Qualco
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
mm or Samsung baseband processor. The virtual modem reports a valid IMEI from a pool of legitimate IMEIs, responds to network registration requests with synthetic but plausible cellular network data, and routes any actual data traffic through the network 
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 in\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 terface assigned to Android. The virtual modem's responses are timed and parameterized to match the behavior of a real baseband processor as closely as possible.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 The second category is the sensor suite. A laptop has a much smaller set of sensors than a phone \hich\f46 \emdash \loch\f46 
 no gyroscope, no magnetometer, no proximity sensor, sometimes no accelerometer. AETHER's virtual sensor subsystem generates synthetic sensor data using phys\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
ically realistic models. Accelerometer readings include thermal noise generated from a Gaussian distribution with parameters matching specific Bosch BMI160 or InvenSense MPU6500 sensors that are common in real Android phones. Gyroscope readings include dr
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 if\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
t modeled as a random walk with the correct integration characteristics. Magnetometer readings include realistic deviation from true magnetic north plus appropriate noise. The data is generated in real time at the polling rates real sensors use, and the A
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 PI responses match the timing and format that real sensor drivers produce.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
The third category is phone-specific peripherals like the fingerprint sensor and the front-facing camera. These are simulated as virtual devices that report not-currently-available status when queried. Apps that depend on these features will see them as p
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 resent but inactive, which is a normal state on real devices when the user has disabled them or when they are obscured. Here\hich\f46 \rquote \loch\f46 s where this is completely possible:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af15\afs26 
\ltrch\fcs0 \fs26\kerning0\loch\af15\hich\af15\dbch\af15\insrsid11555524 \loch\af15\hich\af15\dbch\f15 \u8232\'3f}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af44\afs26 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f44\fs26\kerning0\insrsid11555524 \hich\af44\dbch\af31505\loch\f44 Phone Hardware Bridge Mode}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af46\afs26 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\fs26\kerning0\insrsid11555524 
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
For users who possess a physical Android device and wish to achieve maximum hardware fidelity beyond what software simulation can provide, AETHER offers Phone Hardware Bridge Mode. When the user connects a real Android phone to the laptop via USB and inst
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 alls the AETHER companion app, the virtual Android partition can replace its simulated hardware responses with live data sourced directly from the physical phone.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
In this mode, the gyroscope, accelerometer, and magnetometer data feeding into the Android partition's sensor stack come in real time from the phone's actual MEMS sensors rather than from AETHER's mathematical simulation. The data carries the exact therma
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 l noise characteristics, drift patterns, and calibration signatures of that specific physical sensor, because it is that specific physical sensor producing it.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
The IMEI, device serial number, and all hardware identifiers reported by the Android partition are queried live from the connected phone rather than generated synthetically. These identifiers are real, registered, and verifiable in carrier and manufacture
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 r databases because they belong to a real device.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
Cellular connectivity, where required by apps, is routed through the phone's actual modem via standard USB tethering. The cellular radio handling the connection is a real radio on a real registered SIM, not a simulated interface.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 Camera input, where requested by applications running in the partition, can optionally be sourced from the phone's camera hardware, with frames streamed to the partition over USB in real time.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
The phone's application processor bears negligible load throughout all of this. Identity queries are infrequent string lookups. Sensor streaming is lightweight USB data transfer. The phone remains fully usable for any simultaneous task. All computation 
\hich\f46 \emdash \loch\f46  \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 game logic, rendering, network packet processing \hich\f46 \emdash \loch\f46  happens entirely on the laptop's hardware. The phone is a hardware witness, not a computational participant.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 Bridge Mode is entirely optional. AETHER's simulation is designed to be sufficient without it. Bridge Mode exists for users who want the highest possible fidelity and happen to have a compatible Android device available.

\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sa40\nowidctlpar\wrapdefault\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid10836955 {\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af44\afs32 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f44\fs32\kerning0\insrsid11555524 \hich\af44\dbch\af31505\loch\f44 Chapter 13. GPU Partitioning Through SR-IOV

\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\wrapdefault\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid10836955 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af46\afs26 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\fs26\kerning0\insrsid11555524 \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
Graphics is the most performance-sensitive subsystem in the entire architecture, because a key use case for AETHER is gaming. The graphics partitioning strategy uses a hardware feature called SR-IOV \hich\f46 \emdash \loch\f46 
 Single Root I/O Virtualization \hich\f46 \emdash \loch\f46  that allows a single \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 physical GPU to present itself as multiple independent GPUs to the system.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
When SR-IOV is enabled on a GPU, the GPU's driver subsystem creates a small number of virtual functions, each of which appears to the system as a separate PCI device with its own memory regions, command queues, and interrupt sources. The host operating sy
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
stem sees one or more of these virtual functions and can assign them to different guests. The GPU's hardware enforces isolation between virtual functions, ensuring that work submitted to one cannot interfere with work submitted to another.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
AETHER configures SR-IOV at boot to create two virtual functions on the integrated GPU. One is assigned to Windows, the other to Android. Each guest's graphics driver communicates directly with its assigned virtual function with no software mediation by t
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 he hypervisor. The Android graphics stack \hich\f46 \emdash \loch\f46  Adreno or Mali driver, OpenGL ES library, Vulkan library \hich\f46 \emdash \loch\f46 
 talks to its virtual function exactly as it would to a real GPU. The performance is native; the hypervisor does not see graphics commands.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
Android's graphics driver is selected at AOSP build time to match the virtual function's reported identity. If AETHER configures the Android virtual function to identify as an Adreno 740, the Android image is built with the Adreno graphics driver. The dri
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
ver communicates with what it believes is real Adreno hardware, and at the hardware level, the GPU's SR-IOV implementation responds correctly because the virtual function genuinely presents Adreno-compatible registers and command formats.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
SR-IOV support on consumer ARM laptop GPUs is currently uneven. Snapdragon X Elite's Adreno X1 GPU supports SR-IOV in newer firmware revisions. Apple Silicon GPUs do not expose SR-IOV. Future revisions of AETHER may need to fall back to software-based GPU
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46  sharing using techniques like Intel GVT-g or NVIDIA vGPU, but the architectural target is full SR-IOV passthrough.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sa40\nowidctlpar\wrapdefault\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid10836955 {\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af44\afs32 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f44\fs32\kerning0\insrsid11555524 \hich\af44\dbch\af31505\loch\f44 Chapter 14. Storage Partitioning
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\wrapdefault\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid10836955 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af46\afs26 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\fs26\kerning0\insrsid11555524 \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
Storage is partitioned at the NVMe namespace level. A modern NVMe SSD supports multiple namespaces, each of which appears as a separate block device. AETHER assigns one namespace to Windows and another to Android, and configures the NVMe controller's SR-I
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 OV implementation (where supported) or its built-in namespace isolation to ensure that each guest's NVMe driver can only see and access its assigned namespace.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 The Android namespace is formatted with the Android-standard partition layout \hich\f46 \emdash \loch\f46  boot partition, system partition, vendor partition, userdata partition, and so on \hich\f46 \emdash \loch\f46 
 and contains a complete Android filesystem. The Windows namespace contains a complete Windo\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
ws installation. Neither namespace is visible to the other guest. There is no shared partition, no shared folder, no clipboard sync between guests at the storage level.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
The performance implication is that storage I/O happens at native NVMe speed in both guests, with no hypervisor mediation in the data path. A read or write issued by either guest is dispatched directly to the NVMe controller through the guest's own NVMe d
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 river, executes against the guest's assigned namespace, and returns directly to the guest. AETHER is not involved.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sa40\nowidctlpar\wrapdefault\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid10836955 {\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af44\afs32 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f44\fs32\kerning0\insrsid11555524 \hich\af44\dbch\af31505\loch\f44 Chapter 15. Network Partitioning
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\wrapdefault\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid10836955 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af46\afs26 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\fs26\kerning0\insrsid11555524 \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
The networking strategy depends on the laptop's hardware. Most ARM laptops have a single wireless network adapter, which presents a partitioning challenge because two guests cannot share a single radio without paravirtualization or hardware support for SR
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 -IOV on the adapter.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 AETHER's preferred configuration uses laptops that have separate WiFi and cellular modems, or laptops with WiFi adapters that support SR-IOV. In the SR-IOV case, the strategy mirrors the GPU strategy \hich\f46 \emdash 
\loch\f46  two virtual functions, one assigned to each guest, wi\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 th isolation enforced in hardware. In the dual-adapter case, the WiFi is assigned to Windows and the cellular modem (where present) is assigned to Android.

\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
For laptops with only a single non-SR-IOV WiFi adapter, AETHER falls back to a paravirtualized network where the adapter is assigned to one guest and the other guest receives a virtual network interface that tunnels its traffic through the assigned guest.
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46  This is a deliberate compromise reserved for hardware that cannot support proper passthrough. The design goal is to minimize how often this fallback is needed by recommending hardware that supports clean passthrough.

\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sa40\nowidctlpar\wrapdefault\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid10836955 {\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af44\afs32 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f44\fs32\kerning0\insrsid11555524 \hich\af44\dbch\af31505\loch\f44 Chapter 16. USB And Input Routing
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\wrapdefault\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid10836955 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af46\afs26 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\fs26\kerning0\insrsid11555524 \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
USB is partitioned at the controller level, not the device level. A laptop typically has multiple USB controllers \hich\f46 \emdash \loch\f46 
 one for the integrated keyboard and trackpad, one for external USB-A ports, one for USB-C ports. AETHER assigns each controller to a specif\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
ic guest at boot. A keyboard plugged into a port managed by the Android-assigned controller appears in Android only, not in Windows.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
This partitioning is enforced through the SMMU, just like other DMA-capable devices. The Android USB controller's DMA operations are constrained by the SMMU to access only Android memory regions, and the controller's interrupts are routed only to Android 
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 cores. Windows has no visibility into USB activity on the Android-assigned controller and cannot interfere with it.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 For the integrated keyboard and trackpad, AETHER provides a small mechanism for the user to switch which guest currently receives input \hich\f46 \emdash \loch\f46 
 typically a key combination that signals AETHER to reassign the integrated input controller from one guest to the oth\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
er. This is the only point at which AETHER provides a user-facing affordance that crosses the partition boundary, and it does so only for the practical reality that a laptop has only one physical keyboard.
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sa40\nowidctlpar\wrapdefault\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid10836955 {\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af44\afs32 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f44\fs32\kerning0\insrsid11555524 \hich\af44\dbch\af31505\loch\f44 Part V \hich\f44 \emdash \loch\f44 
 The Windows Partition
\par \hich\af44\dbch\af31505\loch\f44 Chapter 17. ARM Tier \hich\f44 \emdash \loch\f44  Hardware And Partition Configuration
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\wrapdefault\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid10836955 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af46\afs26 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\fs26\kerning0\insrsid11555524 \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
On ARM Tier hardware (Snapdragon X Elite / X Plus), AETHER configures the following at boot. All physical CPU cores are assigned to the Android partition. Memory is partitioned between a hypervisor reservation and the Android working set. The GPU SR-IOV v
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 irtual function is configured for Android's Adreno driver. An NVMe namespace is assigned exclusively to the Android filesystem. USB controllers are assigned per-device to Android.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 AETHER constructs device tree blobs describing Android's assigned hardware exactly. The Android bootloader and kernel read these descriptions and load drivers for what they believe is real hardware \hich\f46 \emdash 
\loch\f46  because it is real hardware, passed through directly.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
Stage 2 page tables are programmed at boot to map Android's IPA space to its assigned PA regions. Any out-of-bounds access traps to EL2, where AETHER terminates it. Each device's interrupt lines are configured to route only to Android's assigned cores via
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46  GICv3 virtualization extension. AETHER configures this once at boot; hardware enforces it thereafter.
\par 
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 Chapter 18. x86 Tier \hich\f46 \emdash \loch\f46  DBT And VMCS Configuration
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
On x86 Tier hardware (Intel or AMD), AETHER boots in VMX/SVM root mode directly on silicon with no host OS. The VMCS or VMCB is initialized with host state fields (AETHER's register state restored on every VM exit), guest state fields (Android's initial r
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 egister state), VM-execution controls, and the EPT or NPT root pointing to Android's assigned physical memory region.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
FEX-Emu is initialized as the DBT engine inside the hypervisor. The JIT translation cache is allocated in hypervisor memory, inaccessible to Android. On first execution of each ARM64 basic block, DBT translates it to x86 and caches the result. Subsequent 
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 executions use the cached translation with no re-translation overhead. ARM64 system register accesses are emulated by the DBT engine to return correct values for the emulated CPU model (Cortex-X4).
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
The Android kernel and all userspace code run as ARM64 software throughout. They read ARM64 system registers, execute ARM64 instructions, and receive ARM64 exception semantics. The x86 hardware underneath is completely invisible.
\par 
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 Chapter 19. The Bootloader
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
The Android partition begins its life with an Android-compliant bootloader, specifically a port of U-Boot or a custom bootloader following the Android Verified Boot specification. AETHER loads the bootloader into the Android partition's memory at the entr
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 y point Android expects, and execution begins there at EL1 inside the Android partition's context.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 The bootloader performs the same operations it would on a real Android device. It initializes its view of the platform \hich\f46 \emdash \loch\f46 
 which AETHER has prepared to look like a specific Android device, complete with device tree, ACPI-equivalent hardware description, and\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
 verified boot keys. It verifies the cryptographic signature of the Android boot image. It loads the Linux kernel into memory, places the device tree blob at the address the kernel expects, and transfers execution to the kernel entry point.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 The verified boot subsystem reports a "locked" bootloader state, which is the state real Android devices ship in and the state SafetyNet and similar attestation systems expect. AETHER's bootloader is not actually unlocked 
\hich\f46 \emdash \loch\f46  it cryptographically verifies t\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
he Android image it loads, using keys controlled by AETHER's build system. Because AETHER is the entity that built the Android image and signed it, the verification succeeds, and the bootloader truthfully reports a locked state.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sa40\nowidctlpar\wrapdefault\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid10836955 {\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af44\afs32 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f44\fs32\kerning0\insrsid11555524 \hich\af44\dbch\af31505\loch\f44 Chapter 20. The Linux Kernel
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\wrapdefault\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid10836955 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af46\afs26 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\fs26\kerning0\insrsid11555524 \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
The Linux kernel inside the Android partition is built from the Android Common Kernel source tree, which is Google's curated branch of mainline Linux with Android-specific patches. AETHER builds this kernel for the ARM64 architecture targeting AETHER's vi
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 rtual hardware platform.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
The kernel is configured with drivers for the hardware the Android partition has been assigned. The Adreno GPU driver is included because the Android partition has been given an Adreno virtual function. The Qualcomm WiFi driver or cellular modem driver is
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46  included to match the network hardware. The standard ARM architectural timer driver, GIC driver, and SMMU driver are included because every ARM64 system needs them.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
Crucially, the kernel does not include any AETHER-specific drivers. There is no virtio driver, no paravirtualization client, no hypervisor integration code. The kernel believes it is running on a real ARM64 SoC and uses standard drivers for what it percei
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 ves as standard hardware. This is what makes the partition appear genuine \hich\f46 \emdash \loch\f46 
 every driver in the kernel is a real driver for real hardware, and the hardware those drivers communicate with is either real (passed through) or genuinely simulated to specificat\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 io\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
n (the few paravirtualized devices).
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sa40\nowidctlpar\wrapdefault\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid10836955 {\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af44\afs32 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f44\fs32\kerning0\insrsid11555524 \hich\af44\dbch\af31505\loch\f44 Chapter 21. AOSP And The Android Userspace
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\wrapdefault\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid10836955 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af46\afs26 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\fs26\kerning0\insrsid11555524 \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
Above the kernel runs the Android userspace, built from the Android Open Source Project. The build target is a custom AETHER device configuration that specifies the hardware identity, the included system services, and the preinstalled applications.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 The device configuration tells the AOSP build system that this device has the hardware AETHER's virtual platform exposes \hich\f46 \emdash \loch\f46 
 specific CPU cores, specific GPU, specific sensors, specific identifiers. The build system generates the appropriate }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af46 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\kerning0\insrsid11555524 \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 vendor}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af46\afs26 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f46\fs26\kerning0\insrsid11555524 \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
 partition contents, including the hardware abstraction layer libraries that match this hardware. When Android runs, its userspace HALs talk to the same hardware the kernel drivers do, and the chain from app to kernel to hardware is unbroken Android softw
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 are all the\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46  way down.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
The Android Runtime (ART) compiles applications from DEX bytecode to native ARM64 machine code at install time, just as it does on a real device, and that native code executes directly on the real CPU at native speed. There is no interpretation, no transl
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 ation, no performance penalty. Apps run as fast as they would on a real Android device with equivalent hardware \hich\f46 \emdash \loch\f46 
 and given that the Android partition has access to a Snapdragon X Elite's CPU cores, that means apps run faster than they do on most actual p\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 ho\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 nes.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sa40\nowidctlpar\wrapdefault\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid10836955 {\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af44\afs32 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f44\fs32\kerning0\insrsid11555524 \hich\af44\dbch\af31505\loch\f44 Chapter 22. The microG Substitution
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\wrapdefault\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid10836955 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af46\afs26 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\fs26\kerning0\insrsid11555524 \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
Google Play Services is Google's proprietary collection of cloud-connected services that most Android applications depend on. It provides Google account authentication, push notifications through Firebase Cloud Messaging, location services through the Fus
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 ed Location Provider, advertising identifiers, in-app purchasing, and the Play Integrity API that detects non-certified Android environments.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
AETHER does not include Google Play Services because Google does not license it to non-certified Android implementations, and obtaining certification for a hypervisor-based Android image would require Google's cooperation. Instead, AETHER integrates micro
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 G, an open-source reimplementation of the Google Play Services API surface.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
microG provides API-level compatibility for the most commonly used Google services. Apps that authenticate users through Google Sign-In work because microG implements the same authentication flow. Apps that receive push notifications through FCM work beca
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
use microG's GmsCore reimplements the FCM client. Apps that look up the user's location through the Fused Location Provider receive location data, although the data comes from the microG location backend rather than from Google's servers.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
The Play Integrity API is the hardest case, because its purpose is specifically to detect non-Google Android environments. microG's Play Integrity implementation returns responses indicating an unverified environment, which causes some apps \hich\f46 
\emdash \loch\f46  primarily ba\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 nking apps and certain games with strict integrity requirements \hich\f46 \emdash \loch\f46 
 to refuse to run. For applications that do not check Play Integrity, microG provides full functional compatibility. For applications that do check it, AETHER offers a future path through a \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 co
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 mpatibility shim that responds to integrity checks with cached attestations from real devices, but this remains a research direction rather than a current feature.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sa40\nowidctlpar\wrapdefault\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid10836955 {\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af44\afs32 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f44\fs32\kerning0\insrsid11555524 \hich\af44\dbch\af31505\loch\f44 Chapter 23. The Play Store Question
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\wrapdefault\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid10836955 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af46\afs26 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\fs26\kerning0\insrsid11555524 \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
The Google Play Store, the application AETHER users will most want to install applications from, is itself a Google application that depends on Play Services. Without official Google certification, the Play Store cannot be legitimately included in AETHER'
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 s Android image.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
AETHER addresses this through alternative app sources. The default app store in AETHER is F-Droid, which carries open-source applications and is freely redistributable. For applications not available on F-Droid, AETHER includes Aurora Store, an open-sourc
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
e frontend to the Google Play Store backend that allows users to download Play Store apps using anonymous accounts. Aurora Store provides access to most of the Play Store catalog without requiring AETHER itself to be certified.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
For users who wish to install the genuine Google Play Store, AETHER provides a manual installation path that requires the user to acknowledge the legal and technical implications of running Google's proprietary services on a non-certified Android implemen
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 tation. This path is supported but not the default.
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sa40\nowidctlpar\wrapdefault\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid10836955 {\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af44\afs32 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f44\fs32\kerning0\insrsid11555524 \hich\af44\dbch\af31505\loch\f44 Part VII \hich\f44 \emdash \loch\f44 
 Cross-Cutting Concerns
\par \hich\af44\dbch\af31505\loch\f44 Chapter 24. Performance
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\wrapdefault\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid10836955 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af46\afs26 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\fs26\kerning0\insrsid11555524 \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
The performance philosophy of AETHER is that nothing should be slower than it would be on equivalent native hardware, and many things should be faster because the underlying ARM64 chip in a Snapdragon X Elite is more capable than any phone's chip.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 CPU performance is native. Guests execute their instructions directly on the real CPU at full speed. The hypervisor only intervenes for trapped operations, which are rare during normal application execution.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 Memory performance is native. Stage 2 translation happens in hardware via the MMU's two-stage translation, which is fully pipelined and adds no measurable overhead to normal memory accesses.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 GPU performance is native via SR-IOV. Graphics commands flow from the Android graphics stack directly to the GPU virtual function with no software mediation.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 Storage performance is native via NVMe namespace passthrough. Reads and writes flow from the Android NVMe driver directly to the controller.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 Network performance is native via SR-IOV or dedicated adapter passthrough. Packets flow through the assigned hardware without hypervisor involvement.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 The places where overhead exists are the paravirtualized devices \hich\f46 \emdash \loch\f46  the modem, the sensors, the phone-specific peripherals \hich\f46 \emdash \loch\f46 
 but these are not performance-critical for any normal use case. Reading the gyroscope at one hundred hertz is not bottlenecked by a\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 nything AETHER does.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sa40\nowidctlpar\wrapdefault\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid10836955 {\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af44\afs32 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f44\fs32\kerning0\insrsid11555524 \hich\af44\dbch\af31505\loch\f44 Chapter 25. Security
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\wrapdefault\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid10836955 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af46\afs26 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\fs26\kerning0\insrsid11555524 \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
The security model of AETHER rests on hardware enforcement of partitioning. The SMMU enforces device DMA isolation. Stage 2 translation enforces CPU memory isolation. The GIC enforces interrupt isolation. None of these are software policies that can be by
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 passed by buggy or malicious code in either guest. They are hardware mechanisms that the processor enforces unconditionally.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 The hypervisor itself runs at EL2, above both guests, and its memory is not mapped into either guest's address space. There is no way for code in either guest to read or write hypervisor memory.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
The attack surface of the hypervisor is small by design. The hypervisor exposes no API to its guests beyond what the ARM architecture defines for guest-host communication, and the guest-host communication paths it does expose are minimal \hich\f46 
\emdash \loch\f46  a small number \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 of hypercall handlers for operations that genuinely require hypervisor mediation. Each handler is a few dozen lines of carefully audited code.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
The hypervisor is written in Rust to provide memory safety at the language level for everything outside the few hand-written assembly entry points. The assembly portions are limited to the EL2 exception vectors and the context-switching code, both of whic
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 h are small enough to be audited line by line.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sa40\nowidctlpar\wrapdefault\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid10836955 {\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af44\afs32 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f44\fs32\kerning0\insrsid11555524 \hich\af44\dbch\af31505\loch\f44 Chapter 26. Time
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\wrapdefault\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid10836955 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af46\afs26 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\fs26\kerning0\insrsid11555524 \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
Time deserves its own chapter because it is one of the subtlest aspects of virtualization and one where most hypervisors leak fingerprints.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
Each ARM64 core has an architectural timer that counts cycles since the system started. Guests read this timer to measure elapsed time, and many anti-cheat systems compare timer readings to detect virtualization through inconsistencies. AETHER configures 
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 the virtual architectural timer such that each guest sees a coherent, monotonic time stream that matches what real hardware would produce.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
Because AETHER does not multiplex CPU cores between guests, time in each guest flows continuously and naturally. There are no gaps in the time stream where AETHER took the CPU away to run something else. The Android partition's clock advances at exactly t
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 he rate the real CPU's architectural timer advances. The Windows partition's clock does the same, on its own cores.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
The wall-clock time, separate from the architectural timer, is initialized at boot from the platform's real-time clock and then maintained internally by each guest using its own NTP synchronization through its assigned network interface. AETHER does not p
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 rovide time services to either guest.
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sa40\nowidctlpar\wrapdefault\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid10836955 {\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af44\afs32 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f44\fs32\kerning0\insrsid11555524 \hich\af44\dbch\af31505\loch\f44 Part VIII \hich\f44 \emdash \loch\f44 
 Build And Toolchain
\par \hich\af44\dbch\af31505\loch\f44 Chapter 27. The Build System
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\wrapdefault\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid10836955 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af46\afs26 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\fs26\kerning0\insrsid11555524 \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
AETHER is built from a unified build system that produces three artifacts: the hypervisor binary, the Windows boot configuration, and the Android image. The build system is implemented in a combination of Make, Cargo (for the Rust hypervisor code), and So
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 ong (for the AOSP portion of the Android image). A top-level orchestration script invokes each subsystem in the correct order with the correct configuration.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
The hypervisor source tree is structured as a Rust workspace with separate crates for the EL2 entry code, the Stage 2 translation manager, the SMMU manager, the GIC manager, the device assignment manager, the paravirtualized device implementations, and th
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 e boot orchestration logic. Each crate has its own unit tests, and the workspace as a whole has integration tests that run inside QEMU's virtualization emulation for development.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
The Android image build is performed by a fork of AOSP that includes AETHER's device configuration and the integrated microG components. The fork is rebased regularly against upstream AOSP to incorporate security patches and feature updates.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sa40\nowidctlpar\wrapdefault\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid10836955 {\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af44\afs32 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f44\fs32\kerning0\insrsid11555524 \hich\af44\dbch\af31505\loch\f44 Chapter 28. The Development Workflow
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\wrapdefault\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid10836955 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af46\afs26 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\fs26\kerning0\insrsid11555524 \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
Development happens primarily on x86-64 Linux workstations using cross-compilation toolchains for ARM64. The hypervisor binary is built with the Rust ARM64 target. The Android image is built with AOSP's standard build system targeting AETHER's device conf
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 iguration.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
Testing happens at three levels. Unit tests run on the development machine for individual hypervisor components. Integration tests run the hypervisor inside QEMU's ARM64 system emulation, with simulated guests, on the development machine. Hardware tests r
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 un the full hypervisor on real ARM64 hardware \hich\f46 \emdash \loch\f46  initially development boards like the SolidRun HoneyComb or actual Snapdragon X Elite laptops in a development partition.
\par \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 Continuous integration runs the unit and integration test suites on every commit. Hardware tests run nightly on a small fleet of physical test machines.
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sa40\nowidctlpar\wrapdefault\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid10836955 {\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af44\afs32 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f44\fs32\kerning0\insrsid11555524 \hich\af44\dbch\af31505\loch\f44 Part IX \hich\f44 \emdash \loch\f44  Roadmap

\par \hich\af44\dbch\af31505\loch\f44 Chapter 29. Phase One \hich\f44 \emdash \loch\f44  Foundation
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\wrapdefault\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid10836955 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af46\afs26 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\fs26\kerning0\insrsid11555524 \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
The first phase, estimated at twelve to eighteen months for a small team, produces a hypervisor that boots on real ARM64 hardware, partitions resources between two guests, and runs a minimal Linux guest in each partition. Both guests can execute code, all
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 ocate memory, handle interrupts from their assigned devices, and communicate with simple peripherals through passthrough. There is no Android, no Windows, no graphics \hich\f46 \emdash \loch\f46 
 just two isolated Linux instances proving the hypervisor architecture works end to end.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sa40\nowidctlpar\wrapdefault\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid10836955 {\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af44\afs32 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f44\fs32\kerning0\insrsid11555524 \hich\af44\dbch\af31505\loch\f44 Chapter 30. Phase Two \hich\f44 \emdash 
\hich\af44\dbch\af31505\loch\f44  Windows
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\wrapdefault\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid10836955 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af46\afs26 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\fs26\kerning0\insrsid11555524 \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
The second phase, estimated at six to nine months, gets Windows-on-ARM booting and running in one partition. This requires constructing valid ACPI tables for the Windows partition, ensuring all Windows-required platform services are exposed correctly, and
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46  validating that Windows runs stably with full performance. By the end of phase two, the system is a functional Windows-on-ARM laptop with a sleeping second partition.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sa40\nowidctlpar\wrapdefault\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid10836955 {\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af44\afs32 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f44\fs32\kerning0\insrsid11555524 \hich\af44\dbch\af31505\loch\f44 Chapter 31. Phase Three \hich\f44 \emdash 
\loch\f44  Android Bring-Up
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\wrapdefault\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid10836955 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af46\afs26 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\fs26\kerning0\insrsid11555524 \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
The third phase, estimated at twelve months, brings up Android in the second partition. This requires building AOSP for AETHER's device target, integrating microG, configuring the paravirtualized sensors and modem, setting up GPU passthrough through SR-IO
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 V, and validating that standard Android applications run correctly. By the end of phase three, the system runs both Windows and Android side by side with isolated execution.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sa40\nowidctlpar\wrapdefault\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid10836955 {\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af44\afs32 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f44\fs32\kerning0\insrsid11555524 \hich\af44\dbch\af31505\loch\f44 Chapter 32. Phase Four \hich\f44 \emdash 
\loch\f44  Performance And Compatibility
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\wrapdefault\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid10836955 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af46\afs26 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\fs26\kerning0\insrsid11555524 \hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 
The fourth phase, estimated at twelve months, focuses on performance optimization and application compatibility testing. The graphics path is tuned for native performance. The sensor models are refined against real device measurements. Application compati
\hich\af46\dbch\af31505\loch\f46 bility is validated across the top thousand Play Store applications, with bug fixes for any that misbehave.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sa40\nowidctlpar\wrapdefault\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid10836955 {\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af44\afs32 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f44\fs32\kerning0\insrsid11555524 \hich\af44\dbch\af31505\loch\f44 Chapter 33. Phase Five \hich\f44 \emdash 
\loch\f44  Polish And Release
